						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="italic">Broken slab set up in the backyard of Hosahaṭṭi's house.</hi></p>						

						<p>Amōghavarsha I—A.D. 866.</p>						

						<p>This badly damaged and worn out inscription mentions <hi rend="bold">Amōghavarsha.</hi> Only the following details of the date, <hi rend="italic">viz.,</hi> <hi rend="bold">Vyaya, Jyēshṭha</hi> and <hi rend="bold">grahaṇa</hi> are preserved. The year <hi rend="bold">Vyaya</hi> coincided with <hi rend="bold">A.D. 866-67,</hi> when Amōghavarsha I was ruling. It also coincided with A.D. 927. But in this year, there was no eclipse in the month of Jyēshṭha. In <hi rend="bold">A.D. 866,</hi> however, there was a solar eclipse in Jyēshṭha, <hi rend="italic">i.e.,</hi> on <hi rend="bold">June 16, Sunday.</hi> This probably is the intended date. Hence this record may be assigned to <hi rend="bold">Amōghavarsha I.</hi> The mention of <hi rend="bold">Dēvaṇṇayya</hi> strengthens this surmise for it is known from other records that Dēvaṇṇayya was governing <hi rend="bold">Beḷvola Threehundred</hi> when <hi rend="bold">Amōghavarsha I</hi> was ruling. It also mentions <hi rend="bold">Kundeya-seṭṭi</hi> and the village <hi rend="bold">Chiñchala.</hi></p>						

						</summary>
